array.string: A front handspring on vault is an incredibly important gymnastics skill because some gymansts perform it from level 4 all the way through level 8. While the deductions get stricter as a gymnast progresses through the levels, the skill remains the same. It’s also the basis of some more advanced vaults. So it’s in your best interest to learn how to do a front handspring on vault, and master it early.

A kip is an important skill in gymnastics. Not only do you need it for the level 4 gymnastics routine, but many gymnasts also use a kip as their mount at more advanced optional levels. A kip is a hard skill to learn because it requires a lot of upper-body strength, and the motion is unlike previous skills a gymnast has learned.
Horizontal cast is a cast that reaches 90 degrees on the bars.
Start with doing a cast and then tuck feet in to land on the bar.
Different than a straddle or pike glide kip, this long hang kip is usually done on the higher bar.
Back hip circle is when you start off with a cast and then throw your body backwards around the bar to form a 360 degree motion around the bar.
Starting off with your dominant foot in front, kick back leg as you put down your dominant hand down and simultaneously kick legs over hands and land with the non-dominant foot on the ground.
Leap forward with dominant foot and simultaneously kick back other leg to make 120 degrees.
Forward handstand constitutes of placing thumbs together and palms on the beam and kicking up until legs and arms reach one line.
Split jump requires your two legs to split horizontally while jumping and reaching 120 degrees.

dict.key: cartwheel to side handstand, 1/4 turn dismount

array.string: This is the required dismount for the level 4 beam routine. Cartwheel to a side handstand and a 1/4 turn dismount.
